can Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Burcy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Birch  .","German; Dutch (<b>Van der Burch</b>): variant of   Burg  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Birch","meanings":["English, German, Danish, and Swedish: topographic name for someone who lived by a birch tree or in a birch wood, from an ancient Germanic word meaning ‘birch’ (Old English <i>birce</i>, <i>byrce</i> ‘birch’, Middle High German <i>birche</i>, Old Danish <i>birk</i>). In some cases the German and English name may be derived from any of the places called with this word, such as Birch in Aargau (see   Birke  ) or Birch in Essex. In Swedish, the name is in many instances ornamental."]}]},{"name":"Serlo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Mario, Arturo, Jesus, Luis, Raul, Adan, Adela, Agustin, Azucena, Baldemar, Dalila.  Italian Aldo, Angelo, Carlo, Santo, Vito, Antonio, Carmela, Elvio, Enrico, Franco, Grazia, Mauro.","Italian and Spanish: nickname from Italian and medieval Spanish <i>merlo</i> ‘blackbird’ (from Latin <i>merula</i>). In the Middle Ages this bird seems to have been regarded at times as foolish and gullible, and at other times as cunning and wily. In some cases the surname may have arisen as a metonymic occupational name for a bird catcher. See also   Merle   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Merola","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Marco, Sal, Alfonse, Guido, Lorenzo, Pasquale, Salvatore, Antonio, Carlo, Fiore.","Italian (southern): nickname from Neapolitan <i>merula</i> ‘female blackbird’, from Latin <i>merula</i> (see   Merlo  )."]},{"name":"Merli","meanings":["Usual English form of the Welsh name Myrddin . The name is most famous as that of the legendary magician who guides the destiny of  King Arthur . The English form has been distorted by mediation through Old French sources, which associated the second element with the diminutive suffix <i>-lin</i>."]},{"name":"Merle","meanings":["Probably a contracted form of   Meriel  , but also associated with the small class of girls' names derived from birds, since it is identical in form with Old French <i>merle</i> ‘blackbird’ (Latin <i>merula</i>). The name came to public notice in the 1930s with the actress  Merle Oberon  (  1911–79 , born  Estelle Merle O'Brien Thompson )."]},{"name":"Merlos","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Fidel, Francisco, Jorge, Juan, Lazaro, Manuel, Miguel, Adelso, Alonso, Ana, Angel, Cesar.","Spanish and Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Merlos</i> (see   Merlo  )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":5,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705182,"age":36,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":56,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Serlo de Burcy was born about 1030, in Burcy, Calvados, Normandy, France, his father, Eustace de Burgo, was 27 and his mother, Madeleine de Vesci, was 24. He had at least 2 daughters. He died about 1086, in Blagdon, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 58, and was buried in Axbridge, Somerset, England."},"et":{"about 1030–abt 1086":"umbes 1030–umbes 1086","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1055–1107":"1055–1107","–Female":"Surnud","1005–1057":"1005–1057","1007–1060":"1007–1060","about 1030":"umbes 1030","12 May 1060":"12. mai 1060","1066":"1066","1055":"1055","1021":"1021","abt 1086":"umbes 1086","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","1107":"1107","1007":"1007","1005":"1005","1035":"1035","1057":"1057","3 July 1057":"3. juuli 1057","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Blagdon, Somerset, England":"Blagdon, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burcy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Burcy, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Axbridge, Somerset, England":"Axbridge, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"about 1030–abt 1086":"noin 1030–noin 1086","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1055–1107":"1055–1107","–Female":"Kuollut","1005–1057":"1005–1057","1007–1060":"1007–1060","about 1030":"noin 1030","12 May 1060":"12. toukokuuta 1060","1066":"1066","1055":"1055","1021":"1021","abt 1086":"noin 1086","1086":"1